 Sussex), Ford in Sefton (Lancashire), Ford in Crediton and Ford in Holcombe Rogus (both Devon), Ford in Litton and Ford in Wiveliscombe (both Somerset).","Irish: Anglicized form (quasi-translation) of various Gaelic names, for example <b>MacGiolla na Naomh</b> ‘son of <i>Gilla na Naomh</i>’ (a personal name meaning ‘servant of the saints’), <b>Mac Conshámha</b> ‘son of <i>Conshnámha</i>’ (a personal name composed of the elements <i>con</i> ‘dog’ + <i>snámh</i> ‘to swim’), in all of which the final syllable was wrongly thought to be <i>áth</i> ‘ford’, and <b>Ó Fuar(th)áin</b> (see   Foran  ).","Americanized form of French   Faure   ‘blacksmith’."],"variants":[{"name":"Forth","meanings":["English: variant of   Ford   1.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by a ford, Middle High German <i>vort</i>, <i>vurt</i>, Middle Low German <i>vorde</i> ‘ford, entrance way’, or a habitational name from a place in Franconia or in former Pomerania (now Poland) named Forth."]},{"name":"Foard","meanings":["English: variant of   Ford  ."]},{"name":"Forde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Declan, Dermot, Aine, Fionnuala, Liam, Nuala.","English and Irish: variant of   Ford   1 and 2. This is a very common spelling in Ireland.","Norwegian (<b>Førde</b>): habitational name from any of numerous farmsteads named Førde (there are eleven on the west coast), from Old Norse <i>fyrthi</i>, dative of <i>fjǫrthr</i> ‘fjord’."]},{"name":"Foran","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Fuartháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Fuarthán</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>fuar</i> ‘cold’. The word <i>fuarán</i> also means ‘spring’ or ‘pool’. The form <i>Fuarthán</i> was understood as <i>fuarathán</i> ‘cold little ford’, and the name has thus sometimes been translated into English as   Ford  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Ford was born in 1387. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Alexander Featherstone. She died in 1452, in Stanhope, Durham, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1387–1452":"1387–1452","1385–1463":"1385–1463","1410–1435":"1410–1435","1411–Female":"1411–Surnud","1435":"1435","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","25 May 1435":"25. mai 1435","1387":"1387","1452":"1452","1463":"1463","1385":"1385","Stanhope, Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, England","Stanhope Hall, Stanhope, Bishopric Of Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stanhope Hall, Bishopric of Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stanhope Hall, Stanhope, Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1387–1452":"1387–1452","1385–1463":"1385–1463","1410–1435":"1410–1435","1411–Female":"1411–Kuollut","1435":"1435","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","25 May 1435":"25. toukokuuta 1435","1387":"1387","1452":"1452","1463":"1463","1385":"1385","Stanhope, Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, England","Stanhope Hall, Stanhope, Bishopric Of Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stanhope Hall, Bishopric of Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stanhope Hall, Stanhope, Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1387–1452":"1387–1452","1385–1463":"1385–1463","1410–1435":"1410–1435","1411–Female":"1411–Décédée","1435":"1435","1411":"1411","1410":"1410","25 May 1435":"25 mai 1435","1387":"1387","1452":"1452","1463":"1463","1385":"1385","Stanhope, Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Angleterre","Stanhope Hall, Stanhope, Bishopric Of Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Stanhope Hall, Bishopric of Durham, England":"Stanhope, Durham, Angleterre